To create a JavaScript function that determines whether two input strings contain the same characters in the same order, you can simply compare the two strings directly. If they are identical, they will have the same characters in the same order. Here's how you can do it:

```javascript
function areStringsEqual(str1, str2) {
    return str1 === str2;
}

// Example usage:
const string1 = "hello";
const string2 = "hello";
const string3 = "world";

console.log(areStringsEqual(string1, string2)); // Output: true
console.log(areStringsEqual(string1, string3)); // Output: false
```

In this function, `areStringsEqual`, we use the strict equality operator (`===`) to compare the two input strings. If `str1` and `str2` are identical—meaning they have the same characters in the same order—the function will return `true`. Otherwise, it will return `false`. This is a simple and effective way to determine if two strings are equal in content and order.
